04975nam a22006495i 9780226449845DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018000463  a9780226449845  a(DE-B1597)568176  a(OCoLC)1198929281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQH45.5b.C78 2018 4aQH45.5b.C78 2018 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a5082231 aCrump, Marty, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Year with Nature :bAn Almanac /cMarty Crump. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b150 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tDaily Entries. Part 1 -- tDaily Entries. Part 2 -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA Year with Nature is an almanac like none you’ve ever seen: combining science and aesthetics, it is a daily affirmation of the extraordinary richness of biodiversity and our enduring beguilement by its beauty. With a text by herpetologist and natural history writer Marty Crump and a cornucopia of original illustrations by Bronwyn McIvor, this quirky "idian reverie gazes across the globe, media, and time as it celebrates date-appropriate natural topics ranging from the founding of the National Park Service to annual strawberry, garlic, shrimp, hummingbird, and black bear festivals. With Crump, we mark the publication of classics like Carson’s Silent Spring and White’s Charlotte’s Web, and even the musical premiere of Tchaikovsky’s Swan Lake. We note the discovery of the structure of DNA and the mountain gorilla, the rise of citizen science projects, and the work of people who’ve shaped how we view and protect nature—from Aristotle to E. O. Wilson. Some days feature US celebrations, like National Poinsettia Day and National Cat Day; others highlight country-specific celebrations, like Australia’s Wombat Day and Thailand’s Monkey Buffet Festival, during which thousands of macaques feast on an ornately arranged spread of fruits and vegetables. Crump also highlights celebrations that span borders, from World Wildlife Conservation Day to International Mountain Day and global festivities for snakes, sea turtles, and chocolate. Interweaving fascinating facts on everything from jellyfish bodies to monthly birth flowers with folkloric entries featuring the Loch Ness Monster, unicorns, and ancient Greek, Roman, and Egyptian mythology, the almanac is as exhaustive as it is enchanting. A Year with Nature celebrates the wonder and beauty of our natural world as we have expressed it in visual arts, music, literature, science, natural history, and everyday experience. But more than this, the almanac’s vignettes encourage us to contemplate how we can help ensure that future generations will be able to enjoy the landscapes and rich biodiversity we so deeply cherish.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnimalsvMiscellanea. 0aAnimals-Miscellanea. 0aNatural historyvMiscellanea. 0aNatural history-Miscellanea. 0aNature conservationvMiscellanea. 0aNature conservation-Miscellanea. 0aNaturevMiscellanea. 0aNaturexFolklorevMiscellanea. 0aNature-Folklore-Miscellanea. 0aNature-Miscellanea. 0aPlantsvMiscellanea. 0aPlants-Miscellanea. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  anature, biology, science, scientific studies, almanac, handbook, aesthetics, daily affirmation, biodiversity, natural history, herpetology, herpetologist, illustrated text, national park services, festivals, visual arts, musics, literature, everyday experiences, conservation, folklore, celebrations, global perspective, international approach.1 aMcIvor, Bronwyn.08iTitle is part of eBook packag